This is exactly where enterprise architecture gets messy, and your concern about "overhead and rework at every layer" is the most common reason these zero-trust models fail in implementation. If we force every microservice developer to write 500 lines of code just to authenticate a request, delivery grinds to a halt.
To solve this, we must completely separate two concepts in our mental model: System Identity (Machine-to-Machine) and Subject Identity (The User).
Here is the field-tested, ARB-approved approach used in Tier-1 banks to maintain strict Zero Trust without crippling developer velocity.
The Golden Rule of Identity Propagation
System Identity (mTLS) is handled by the Infrastructure (Gateways and Service Mesh). Application code never sees or cares about this.
Subject Identity (Internal JWT) is passed down the chain via HTTP headers (e.g., Authorization: Bearer <Internal-JWT>). Every layer mathematically verifies the token, but only the final Microservice/PBC performs business authorization.
The Step-by-Step Chain of Trust
Let’s trace a request from the Cloud Gateway all the way to the Microservice/PBC.
Hop 1: Cloud API GW ➔ DC Ingress API GW
System Identity: DC Ingress GW authenticates the Cloud GW via mTLS. (Proves: "This traffic actually came from our cloud edge, not a hacker inside our network").
Subject Identity: The Cloud GW passes the public external JWT. The DC Ingress GW validates it, and performs a Token Exchange. It mints a new, short-lived Internal JWT signed by the bank's internal PKI.
Overhead: High. But it only happens once at the physical perimeter.
Hop 2: DC Ingress API GW ➔ Domain API GW
System Identity: The Domain GW authenticates the DC Ingress GW via mTLS. (Proves: "This traffic came through the official border control").
Subject Identity: The DC Ingress GW passes the Internal JWT in the header. The Domain GW mathematically verifies the signature of the Internal JWT using cached public keys (JWKS).
Authorization: Coarse-grained only. The Domain GW checks standard scopes: "Does this token have the payments:write scope?" If yes, it routes it. It does not look at account numbers or business rules.
Overhead: Near-zero. Validating a JWT signature locally takes microseconds.
Hop 3: Domain API GW ➔ Microservice / PBC
System Identity: Handled by a Service Mesh (e.g., Istio, Linkerd) injecting an Envoy sidecar. The sidecar authenticates the Domain GW via mTLS automatically. Your Java/Go/C# code does absolutely nothing here.
Subject Identity: The Microservice receives the request with the Internal JWT. It uses a standard library (like Spring Security) to verify the signature (again, microseconds).
Authorization (The Business Logic): The Microservice extracts the user_id from the JWT and performs Fine-Grained Authorization. It asks the database: "Does user 12345 actually own Account 9876?" ---
How We Eliminate the "Overhead & Rework"
If every layer is authenticating the user, why isn't it slow, and why isn't it a massive rework for developers?
We Never "Call Home" for Token Validation: After the DC Ingress Gateway mints the Internal JWT, no downstream component (Domain GW or PBC) makes a network call to an Identity Provider to validate it. They use Offline Signature Verification. They cache the public key (JWKS) and verify the math locally. This adds ~1-2 milliseconds of total latency across the whole chain.
Infrastructure Offloading (Sidecars):
Developers do not write mTLS code, certificate rotation code, or network encryption code. The Service Mesh (Sidecar) handles the System Identity layer transparently.
Standardized Frameworks:
The bank provides a core library (e.g., a standard Maven/npm package). The developer simply annotates their PBC method with @PreAuthorize("#accountId == authentication.principal.id"). The framework handles parsing the Internal JWT from the header.
Summary: Who Authenticates Whom?
To directly answer your question:
Gateways authenticate Gateways (System Identity / mTLS).
Gateways verify the User Token Signature to ensure the token isn't forged (Zero Trust).
Only the PBC / Microservice AUTHORIZES the User against actual business data (Account ownership, balance limits, entitlements).
