Architecture Review Board (ARB) - Objection Handling Guide

Topic: Hybrid API Gateway Routing & Identity Propagation

This document prepares the architecture team for common objections raised by Security, Networking, and Legacy Enterprise Architecture teams regarding the proposed API routing and Zero Trust identity model.

Part 1: Information Security (InfoSec) Objections

Objection 1: "Why do we need a Token Exchange at the DC Gateway? Why can't we just pass the Okta/Azure AD JWT directly to the backend microservice?"

The Challenger: Identity & Access Management (IAM) Team / SecOps.
The Rationalization:

Audience Restriction (The "Confused Deputy"): Public JWTs have a broad audience claim (e.g., aud: bank-public-api). If an internal microservice accepts this broad token, and that microservice is compromised, the attacker can replay that token against any other internal service. Token Exchange mints an internal JWT with a strict, narrow audience (e.g., aud: legacy-payments-core).

Vendor Lock-in & Abstraction: Legacy systems (Mainframes) or heavily isolated domains should not need to know the cryptographic keys of external providers like Okta or Apple. The DC Gateway abstracts external identity, allowing the bank to swap public IDPs without touching hundreds of internal microservices.

Objection 2: "If the Internal JWT is verified offline by the microservice, how do we revoke it immediately if a user is compromised?"

The Challenger: Cyber Threat/SOC Team.
The Rationalization:

Short Time-to-Live (TTL): Internal JWTs minted by the DC Gateway are configured with an extremely short TTL (e.g., 3 to 5 minutes). By the time a session revocation event is processed, the internal token has usually expired.

Continuous Evaluation: For critical high-value transactions (e.g., wire transfers > $100k), the Domain API Gateway uses a specialized filter to check a high-speed distributed cache (Redis) for a "Token Blocklist" before processing, providing instant kill-switch capabilities without adding overhead to standard read queries.

Objection 3: "Having three layers of Gateways increases our attack surface."

The Challenger: Network Security / Perimeter Team.
The Rationalization:

Compartmentalization: It actually decreases the systemic blast radius. A vulnerability in the Cloud WAF/Gateway exposes the edge, but the attacker still faces the DC Gateway's mTLS requirement. If they bypass that, they face the Domain Gateway's strict internal signature validation.

Defense in Depth: This is the literal definition of Defense in Depth. Compromising one layer does not yield access to the data layer.

Part 2: Enterprise Architecture (EA) & Engineering Objections

Objection 4: "We already invested millions in a centralized Enterprise Service Bus (ESB) and SOA appliances. Why do we need Domain API Gateways?"

The Challenger: Legacy Integration Architects / ESB Center of Excellence.
The Rationalization:

The Centralized Bottleneck: An ESB is a monolithic architecture. If the payments team deploys a bad routing rule, the ESB crashes, and the digital channels team (who share the ESB) also goes down.

Domain-Driven Autonomy: Domain API Gateways (e.g., Envoy sidecars or Spring Cloud Gateway) are lightweight and decoupled. They allow individual product teams to deploy, rate-limit, and scale their APIs independently, matching modern Agile/DevOps velocity.

The Compromise (Strangler Fig): We are not turning off the ESB tomorrow. The ESB will remain behind the DC Ingress Gateway to handle legacy XML/SOAP translations, while new microservices will use Domain Gateways.

Objection 5: "mTLS between Gateways AND offline JWT verification will add too much latency. We have strict 50ms SLAs."

The Challenger: Performance Engineering / SREs.
The Rationalization:

mTLS Connection Pooling: The TLS handshake is expensive (~20-30ms), but it is not paid per request. The Cloud API Gateway and DC API Gateway maintain persistent, keep-alive connection pools. The per-request encryption overhead of AES-GCM is microseconds.

JWT Math is Cheap: Verifying an HMAC or RSA signature locally on modern CPUs takes ~0.1 to 0.5 milliseconds.

Net Impact: The entire security overhead (mTLS + Token Exchange + Offline Verification) adds less than 4 milliseconds to the total request lifecycle. This is a negligible price to pay for Zero Trust compliance.

Objection 6: "If Cloud-Native apps don't route to the DC, but legacy apps do, developers have to write different code depending on where the API lives."

The Challenger: Lead Developers / Platform Engineering.
The Rationalization:

Global Server Load Balancing (GSLB) & Service Mesh: Developers will never hardcode IP addresses or DC-specific URLs. All API calls hit a vanity internal URL (e.g., api.internal.bank/payments).

The underlying DNS/GSLB or Cloud Service Mesh automatically routes the traffic to the Cloud Domain Gateway or the DC Ingress Gateway based on where the workload currently lives. The developer's HTTP client logic remains exactly the same.

